:::summary
Francesco Petrarca (1304–1374), known as Petrarch, is celebrated as the "Father of Humanism" — the Italian poet and scholar who first articulated the Renaissance ideal of recovering the wisdom of ancient Greece and Rome as a guide for human flourishing. His *Canzoniere*, a collection of 366 poems addressed to a woman named Laura, established the Petrarchan sonnet as the dominant lyric form in European poetry for three centuries. His passion for classical Latin literature, his insistence on elegant style, and his vision of a civilization renewed through contact with antiquity made him the founding figure of the Renaissance and one of the most influential intellectuals in Western history.
:::

